<h2 id="Syntax"><nobr>Syntax</nobr></h2>

<div>
<pre class="twopartsyntaxbox"><nobr>Formal grammar: [ above | below | right | left ]? &lt;length&gt;? &lt;image&gt;?
</nobr></pre>

<div class="where">
<h3 id="Values"><nobr>Values</nobr></h3>

<dl><dt><nobr><code>above</code><em>, </em><code>below</code><em>, </em><code>right</code><em>, </em><code>left</code></nobr></dt>
 <dd><nobr>Are keywords indicating in which direction the reflection is to happen.</nobr></dd>
 <dt><nobr><code>&lt;length&gt;</code></nobr></dt>
 <dd><nobr>Indicates the size of the reflection.</nobr></dd>
 <dt><nobr><code>&lt;image&gt;</code></nobr></dt>
 <dd><nobr>Describes the mask to be applied to the reflection.</nobr></dd>
</dl></div>

<dl/><h2 id="Specifications" name="Specifications"><nobr>Specifications</nobr></h2>

<p><nobr>This property is not on the standard track and will not be part of CSS. The standard way to do reflection in CSS is to use the CSS <a href="/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/element" title="The documentation about this has not yet been written; please consider contributing!"><code>element()</code></a> function.</nobr></p>

